{
  "texts": [
    "ML-based approaches offer new approaches for predicting execution times, addressing the inherent complexities and variabilities of existing computing systems.",
    "The advantages of leveraging ML in WCET estimations include adaptability and precision, and efficiency in analysis.",
    "ML models thrive on the dynamic nature of computing systems, offering tailored WCET estimates that reflect the specificities of the hardware and software under consideration [87].",
    "Additionally, by not requiring exhaustive path analysis, ML-based methods can speed up the WCET estimation process, making them ideal for time-constrained development cycles [88].",
    "The exploration of ML in WCET estimation has yielded novel approaches, such as hybrid models that blend static analysis with ML predictions to cover a broader execution spectrum with enhanced accuracy [88].Huybrechts [89] employs a hybrid methodology that combines ML with traditional static and measurement-based analysis techniques to predict WCET and Worst-case Energy Consumption (WCEC)."
  ]
}